\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The fate deck is used to create characters, every step in the character generation, is determined using the fate deck, the order of precedence is not used except for Red Jokers being the top of the tables that are used to determine the scores, with the Black Joker at the bottom if the character is to be a light character, with the Black joker on top and the red on bottom if they are to be a dark character, if the character is to be neutral then the player chooses which side to favor.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When a character of the light draws from the fate deck they do so with the High King (Red Joker) and the suit order of precedence goes Hearts, Diamonds, Clubs, Spades with the Lord of the Underworld Black Joker the worst card they could pull, dark characters order of precedence is Lord of the Underworld Spades, Clubs, Diamonds, Hearts and the High King the worst card they could pull. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In the case of a neutral character before play begins in a session the player choose to favour light or dark in that session.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When using the fate deck to pass a failed check of the dice, a skill check requires the player to choose a colour or suit depending on the difficulty of the test, easy and intermediate colour can be chosen, if the player is a Light Character and the High king (red joker) is pulled it is a pass no matter the difficulty and their fate point is refunded, if the Lord of the Tyranny (black joker) is pulled a further fate point is lost and it fails and vice versa if the character is a dark character. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If it is an opposed check the GM and player both draw a card the Highest card wins, if the player character is of the light, in the event the player or GM pulls the high king it scores a critical pass and the fate point is refunded, if the GM or player pulls the Lord of Tyranny it causes a critical fail and a 2nd fate point is lost. If the player character is a dark character or a neutral player favouring the dark then this is reversed.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 so if the player is light and pulls a 10 of hearts and the GM pulls a 10 of clubs the player wins but if the player pulls a 10 of Diamonds and the GM the 10 of Spades it's the GM that wins, in the event of a draw you draw a second card and whomever pulls the highest card wins, Black and red jokers don't count for adding or subtracting fate points but do for order of precedence if drawn.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
